---
import PageShell from '../../components/PageShell.astro';
import CTABox from '../../components/CTABox.astro';
import ComparisonTable from '../../components/ComparisonTable.astro';

const tocItems = [
  { id: 'top-picks', text: 'Our Top Picks', level: 2 },
  { id: 'leaving-china', text: 'Leaving Chinese Healthcare', level: 2 },
  { id: 'language-support', text: 'Mandarin Language Support', level: 2 },
  { id: 'comparison-table', text: 'Quick Comparison', level: 2 },
  { id: 'detailed-reviews', text: 'Detailed Reviews', level: 2 },
  { id: 'popular-destinations', text: 'Popular Destinations', level: 2 },
  { id: 'faqs', text: 'Common Questions', level: 2 },
];

const relatedLinks = [
  { title: 'Cigna Global Review', href: '/providers/cigna-global' },
  { title: 'Bupa Global Review', href: '/providers/bupa-global' },
  { title: 'Best US Coverage Insurance', href: '/best/us-coverage-insurance' },
  { title: 'Best Asia Insurance', href: '/best/asia-insurance' },
  { title: 'Best Australian Expat Insurance', href: '/best/australian-expat-insurance' },
];

const comparisonColumns = [
  { key: 'provider', header: 'Provider' },
  { key: 'mandarinSupport', header: 'Mandarin Support' },
  { key: 'usCoverage', header: 'US Coverage' },
  { key: 'chinaCoverage', header: 'China Coverage' },
  { key: 'price', header: 'Starting Price' },
];

const comparisonRows = [
  { provider: 'Cigna Global', mandarinSupport: 'Full', usCoverage: 'Strong', chinaCoverage: 'Add-on', price: '$200/mo' },
  { provider: 'Bupa Global', mandarinSupport: 'Yes', usCoverage: 'Excellent', chinaCoverage: 'Add-on', price: '$220/mo' },
  { provider: 'MSH International', mandarinSupport: 'Full', usCoverage: 'Good', chinaCoverage: 'Add-on', price: '$180/mo' },
  { provider: 'Now Health', mandarinSupport: 'Full', usCoverage: 'Good', chinaCoverage: 'Included', price: '$190/mo' },
  { provider: 'Allianz Care', mandarinSupport: 'Limited', usCoverage: 'Good', chinaCoverage: 'Add-on', price: '$190/mo' },
];
---

<PageShell
  title="Best Health Insurance for Chinese Expats 2026"
  description="Compare international health insurance for Chinese expats. Find coverage with Mandarin support for the US, Canada, Australia, UK, and other popular destinations."
  headline="Best Insurance for Chinese Expats in 2026"
  subheadline="Moving abroad from China requires careful insurance planning. Here's how to find coverage with Mandarin support that works in your destination."
  heroBackgroundImage="/images/pages/chinese-expat-hero-bg.png"
  tocItems={tocItems}
  relatedLinks={relatedLinks}
  ctaButtonText="Get Cigna Quote →"
  ctaButtonHref="/go/cigna-global"
>
  <h2 id="top-picks">Our Top Picks</h2>
  <p>
    Chinese expats are among the largest expat populations globally, concentrated in the US, Canada, Australia, UK, and Singapore. Mandarin-language support and strong networks in these destinations are essential. Here's what we recommend:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Cigna Global:</strong> Best overall for Chinese expats. Full Mandarin support, strong networks in all major Chinese expat destinations, reliable claims processing.</li>
    <li><strong>Bupa Global:</strong> Premium option with excellent US, UK, and Australian networks. Mandarin support available.</li>
    <li><strong>MSH International:</strong> Strong Mandarin support with good global coverage. Popular among Chinese expats in Europe.</li>
    <li><strong>Now Health:</strong> Asia-focused with excellent Mandarin service. Includes China coverage automatically.</li>
    <li><strong>Allianz Care:</strong> Good European coverage, though Mandarin support is more limited.</li>
  </ul>

  <CTABox
    title="Mandarin Support Matters"
    description="Navigating healthcare in a foreign language is stressful, especially during emergencies. Prioritize insurers with 24/7 Mandarin-speaking support lines and Mandarin claims processing."
    buttonText="Get Mandarin-Supported Quote"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna-global"
    variant="highlight"
  />

  <h2 id="leaving-china">Leaving Chinese Healthcare</h2>
  <p>
    China's healthcare system is evolving rapidly, with urban public insurance (城镇医疗保险) and rural schemes (新农合). Here's what happens when you leave:
  </p>

  <h3>Urban Employee Insurance</h3>
  <p>
    If you were covered through your employer (职工医疗保险), coverage ends when employment ends. There's no mechanism to continue this abroad. Your medical account balance typically cannot be withdrawn but remains for future use if you return and rejoin.
  </p>

  <h3>Urban Resident Insurance</h3>
  <p>
    Self-paid resident insurance (城镇居民医疗保险) is linked to hukou registration. Once you leave China, this coverage doesn't follow you. You'll need to re-enroll when you return.
  </p>

  <h3>Private Chinese Insurance</h3>
  <p>
    Chinese private insurance (Ping An, China Life, PICC) typically has limited international coverage—usually only 30-90 days of emergency treatment abroad. For long-term stays, you need dedicated international coverage.
  </p>

  <h3>Social Insurance Contributions</h3>
  <p>
    Your pension contributions (养老保险) remain in the system. China has limited social security agreements with other countries, so coordination is less developed than in Europe. Consult with a Chinese tax advisor about your specific situation.
  </p>

  <h2 id="language-support">Mandarin Language Support</h2>
  <p>
    Language support is critical for Chinese expats. Healthcare situations are stressful, and miscommunication can have serious consequences. Here's what to look for:
  </p>

  <h3>What Good Mandarin Support Includes</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>24/7 Mandarin-speaking emergency hotline</li>
    <li>Claims processing in Mandarin</li>
    <li>Mandarin policy documents and member materials</li>
    <li>Mandarin-speaking case managers for complex situations</li>
    <li>Translation assistance at hospitals when needed</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Provider Comparison</h3>
  <p>
    Cigna, Bupa, and MSH have the strongest Mandarin support among major international insurers. Now Health, being Asia-focused, also provides excellent Chinese-language service. Allianz and some other European insurers have more limited Mandarin capabilities.
  </p>

  <div class="bg-amber-50 border border-amber-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-amber-900 mb-2">Finding Chinese-Speaking Doctors</h3>
    <p class="text-amber-800">
      Major cities with large Chinese populations (Los Angeles, San Francisco, Vancouver, Sydney, London) have Chinese-speaking doctors and clinics. Your insurer can help locate them, or check local Chinese community directories.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2 id="comparison-table">Quick Comparison</h2>
  <ComparisonTable columns={comparisonColumns} rows={comparisonRows} />

  <h2 id="detailed-reviews">Detailed Reviews</h2>

  <h3>Cigna Global</h3>
  <p>
    Cigna Global is our top recommendation for Chinese expats. They offer comprehensive Mandarin support including 24/7 hotlines, Mandarin claims processing, and Mandarin-speaking case managers. Networks are strong in all major Chinese expat destinations—US, Canada, Australia, UK, and Singapore.
  </p>

  <p>
    Plans come in three tiers (Silver, Gold, Platinum) with coverage up to unlimited. Direct billing works at major hospitals worldwide. China coverage can be added for visits home.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Chinese expats who want comprehensive coverage with full Mandarin support.
  </p>

  <h3>Bupa Global</h3>
  <p>
    Bupa Global offers premium international coverage with strong networks in the US, UK, and Australia—three of the most popular destinations for Chinese expats. Mandarin support is available, and service quality is high across all touchpoints.
  </p>

  <p>
    Plans are comprehensive, including mental health and maternity coverage. Pricing is higher than competitors but reflects premium service.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Chinese expats who want premium coverage and can afford top-tier pricing.
  </p>

  <h3>MSH International</h3>
  <p>
    MSH International (now part of Diot-Siaci) offers strong international coverage with excellent Mandarin support. Popular among Chinese expats in Europe, they understand the needs of Chinese clients well. Pricing is competitive.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Chinese expats in Europe who want dedicated Mandarin support at reasonable prices.
  </p>

  <h3>Now Health</h3>
  <p>
    Now Health is Asia-focused, making them well-suited to Chinese expats. Mandarin support is excellent, China coverage is included automatically, and they understand Asian healthcare expectations. Good networks throughout Asia and increasingly globally.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Chinese expats who want Asia-focused coverage with automatic China inclusion.
  </p>

  <CTABox
    title="Compare Your Options"
    description="Get quotes from multiple providers to compare pricing and Mandarin support options for your specific destination."
    buttonText="Get Free Quotes"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna-global"
  />

  <h2 id="popular-destinations">Popular Destinations</h2>
  <p>
    Insurance needs vary by destination. Here's what Chinese expats should consider in key locations:
  </p>

  <h3>United States</h3>
  <p>
    The largest destination for Chinese expats. US healthcare is extremely expensive—a hospital stay can easily cost $100,000+. Prioritize insurers with strong US networks and direct billing. California and New York have large Chinese communities with Chinese-speaking doctors.
  </p>

  <h3>Canada</h3>
  <p>
    Provincial healthcare is available to permanent residents, but there's typically a 3-month waiting period. International insurance covers this gap and provides faster access than public healthcare. Vancouver and Toronto have large Chinese communities.
  </p>

  <h3>Australia</h3>
  <p>
    Medicare is available to permanent residents. Visa holders typically need private insurance. Sydney and Melbourne have extensive Chinese healthcare options including traditional Chinese medicine practitioners covered by some insurers.
  </p>

  <h3>United Kingdom</h3>
  <p>
    NHS provides free healthcare to residents, but waiting times can be long. Many Chinese expats supplement with private insurance for faster access. London has numerous Chinese-speaking doctors and clinics.
  </p>

  <h3>Singapore</h3>
  <p>
    Excellent healthcare but expensive. Mandatory CPF contributions cover some healthcare for residents. International insurance provides broader coverage and access to private facilities. Mandarin is widely spoken in healthcare settings.
  </p>

  <h2 id="faqs">Common Questions</h2>

  <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Can I keep my Chinese insurance abroad?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Most Chinese insurance provides only 30-90 days of emergency coverage abroad. For long-term stays, you need dedicated international health insurance.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Is Mandarin support really necessary?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">It depends on your English comfort level. In medical emergencies, communicating in your native language reduces stress and prevents misunderstandings that could affect care.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">What about traditional Chinese medicine?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Coverage varies by insurer. Some plans include TCM as alternative medicine; others don't. Check specific policy details if TCM coverage is important to you.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">How do I get coverage during China visits?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Most international insurers offer China coverage as an add-on. Now Health includes it automatically. Alternatively, get short-term travel insurance for visits.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">What happens to my pension contributions?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Pension contributions remain in the Chinese system. Limited international coordination exists. Consult a Chinese tax advisor about withdrawal or continuation options.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Which insurer is best for the US?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Cigna and Bupa both have excellent US networks. Both offer Mandarin support. Compare quotes based on your age and specific needs.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>Final Verdict</h2>
  <p>
    Chinese expats should prioritize insurers with strong Mandarin support and good networks in their destination country. <strong>Cigna Global</strong> is our top recommendation for comprehensive coverage with full Mandarin service. <strong>Bupa Global</strong> offers premium coverage for those who want the best.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>MSH International</strong> is excellent for Europe, while <strong>Now Health</strong> suits those who want Asia-focused coverage with automatic China inclusion.
  </p>

  <p>
    Don't underestimate US healthcare costs if that's your destination. The monthly premium is a small price compared to the potential cost of a single hospitalization without coverage.
  </p>

</PageShell>
